@node Routing
@section Routing Stumbling Blocks
@cindex routing stumbling blocks
@cindex stumbling blocks, routing

If we wanted to call our back-end server from the client, we would need
to place an anchor tag inside of the @file{App.js} main file in the
@file{client}, and then make an @code{href} with a complete path rather
than a relative path.  However, that would be a mistake because the
production route would be different, and so we would have to change it
before deploying the production app.  We need to find a way to make the
anchor work regardless of which version we were working on, development
or production.

To make this work, our anchor tag would like like:

@code{<a href="/auth/google">Sign In With Google</a>}

As is obvious, the @code{href} is a relative path.

Now, place the following code inside the client @file{package.json}
file:

@example
"proxy": @{
  "/auth/google": @{
    "target": "http://localhost:DEV_PORT"
  @}
@}
@end example

