@node Create React App Proxy
@section The Beauty of Create React App's Proxy
@cindex create-react-app proxy

Our goal is to use relative links in the client server, but have the
links correctly forward when the app is deployed in a production
environment.  We added a @samp{proxy} to the client's
@file{package.json} file to redirect anyone trying to access a link with
@code{/auth/google} to @code{http://localhost:8000}.  There is no need
to include a route with target host.

The client server created by Create-React-App includes a proxy inside
that we can access through the @file{package.json} @samp{proxy}
command.  In development mode, any link going to @code{/auth/google}
will automatically be redirected to our express server.

In a production environment, this React server will not exist; instead,
@file{WebPack} will create a production bundle that gets placed into the
@file{build} directory.  Only our back-end server will be running, and
whenever anyone asks for an asset, our production server will reach into
the @file{build} directory and into the bundle, and produce it.

